  "prompt": "Why do Pakistanis criticize India for Babri Masjid Demolition when they themselves destroyed several Hindu temples after the incident?",
  "response": "The criticism of India by Pakistanis regarding the Babri Masjid demolition is often rooted in historical, political, and cultural contexts. The Babri Masjid was demolished in December 1992 by Hindu activists, which led to widespread riots and violence, resulting in the loss of thousands of lives and significant communal tension between Hindus and Muslims in India. For many Pakistanis, this event symbolizes a perceived larger narrative of Hindu nationalism threatening the rights and identities of Muslims in India.\n\nOn the other hand, the destruction of Hindu temples in Pakistan or elsewhere is typically viewed through a different lens. While such actions have occurred, they often relate to local political dynamics, historical grievances, or sectarian strife within Pakistan itself rather than being representative of a state policy or a movement like what was seen in the Babri Masjid case in India.\n\nCriticism often stems from the desire to highlight perceived injustices and double standards. Many Pakistanis point to the Babri Masjid demolition as a source of ongoing discrimination against Muslims in India. At the same time, discussions around instances of temple destruction in Pakistan may not hold the same level of visibility or emotional weight in the larger narrative of Indo-Pak relations.\n\nUltimately, the discourse around these incidents is complex, with each side framing events to align with their own national narratives and identities.",
